replies.bodyText:
@LuQQiu
I see. Let's say we have a 1m timeout, and the worker heartbeat takes longer than 1m, even though nothing has happened to the master (no failover, no network flakiness). What will happen to the worker? Will it just try to reconnect again?
If the worker heartbeat always takes more than 1m, does that mean that worker will never be able to successfully perform a heartbeat?

@LuQQiu I see. Then, maybe we do want to make the timeout longer.
From an earlier comment, you said typically, when a master does a failover, the worker will immediately know, because the old master would actively reject the connection? Is this correct? That means this timeout will not affect normal failovers, but only unreachable old masters? If this is the case, then this is more reason to make the timeout long.
Thanks for the explanations.
